result.name: China Club

reviews.text: You need membership, or to know a member. Middle couple of floors, in a great old building, in a great location. Old-world dark-wood charm. Great art collection. Small but good bar. Good restaurant including "a noodle making performance" each evening.

The China Club is a retro-chic, Shanghai-style club and restaurant in Hong Kong. It is related to the China Clubs in Singapore and Beijing but is not related to the clubs of the same name in New York City and Berlin, Germany.
Classy Chinese dining at the top of the old Bank of China building. Beautiful art from Chinese artists all over the interior in a beautifully designed 1930s Shanghai Art Deco style interior.

Beautiful decor, enchanting place! A must do in Hong Kong. Our meal was delicious but the service was substandard. We had a fantastic family & friends night nevertheless. 
Side note: Our friends had been praising some sort of live show but apparently that’s no longer on “because too expensive” as we were told. A little surprising considering this place was not cheap.

When I first went to the restaurant, I felt like I was back in the 1850s. It felt as if I had become an English aristocrat. In fact, this restaurant has been run as a social gathering place for British aristocrats. It still maintains that way. So this restaurant is only available for reservation by members. How to become a member is difficult. This is because existing members should recommend it. Luckily, my friend who is a member invited me. There are bar and gallery upstairs. This is the place I want to go again.
